rbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=March 8, 1969|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=10|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|December 23, 1968}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title=Fairbanks Gets Priority in Expanded BIA Program (pt 1)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13291079/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=December 23, 1968|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} and {{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Fairbanks Gets Priority in Expanded BIA Program (pt 2)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13291099/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=December 23, 1968|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1962}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Fates to Return|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13291726/fates_to_return_fairbanks_daily_news/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=July 12, 1962|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=11|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Daily Sitka Sentinel''|1993}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Hickel Names Two Regents|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13319384/hickel_names_two_regents_the_daily/|accessdate=24 August 2017|publisher=[[Daily Sitka Sentinel]]|date=January 19, 1993|location=Sitka, Alaska|page=9|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Wausau Daily Herald''|1978}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Homemakers attend conference|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13291198/wausau_daily_herald/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Wausau Daily Herald]]|date=September 28, 1978|location=Wausau, Wisconsin|page=16|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|February 15, 1968}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Hospital Unit Names 5 Officers|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13295099/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=February 15, 1968|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=7|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} \n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|May 25, 1977}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Indian women meet in June|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13291539/indian_women_meet_in_june_fairbanks/|accessdate=24 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=May 25, 1977|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=7|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Great Falls Tribune''|1978}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Isolation seen as plague of rural women|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13291685/great_falls_tribune/|accessdate=24 August 2017|agency=[[New York Times News Service]]|publisher=[[Great Falls Tribune]]|date=February 28, 1978|location=Great Falls, Montana|page=10|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1954}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Mary Jane Evans Married to Hugh Fate, Jr. Oct. 29|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13290131/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=November 9, 1954|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=5|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite web|ref={{harvid|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Mary Jane (Evans) Fate|url=http://alaskawomenshalloffame.org/alumnae/name/mary-jane-fate/|website=Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|publisher=Alaska Women's Network|accessdate=23 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823180558/http://alaskawomenshalloffame.org/alumnae/name/mary-jane-fate/|archivedate=23 August 2017|location=Anchorage, Alaska|date=2014}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1970}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Mrs. Fate helps to organize North American Indian unit|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13291646/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=24 August 2017|publisher=[[Fairbanks Daily News Miner]]|date=August 27, 1970|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1967}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Native Village Readied for A-67|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13293485/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=January 19, 1967|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=7|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Albuquerque Journal''|1975}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Passes Gavel to New President|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13290573/albuquerque_journal/|accessdate=24 August 2017|newspaper=[[The Albuquerque Journal]]|date=June 22, 1975|location=Albuquerque, New Mexico|page=24|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1966}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Project Pushed by Volunteers|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13296726/project_pushed_by_volunteers_fairbanks/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=January 31, 1966|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1964}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Resolution Asks State to Recognize Problem|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13296484/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=23 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=October 29, 1964|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=9|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref={{harvid|''The San Saba News and Star''|1976}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Resolution Asks State to Recognize Problem|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13290510/the_san_saba_news_and_star/|accessdate=24 August 2017|publisher=The San Saba News and Star|date=October 21, 1976|location=San Saba, Texas|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://vilda.alaska.edu/cdm/ref/collection/cdmg2/id/3786 photograph]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Alaska Women's Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fate, Mary Jane}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alaskan Athabaskan people]]\n[[Category:Female Native American leaders]]\n[[Category:American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:Alaska Native activists]]\n[[Category:Native American women in politics]]\n[[Category:American women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:People from Fairbanks, Alaska]]\n[[Category:People from Yukon\u2013Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:University of Alaska Fairbanks alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alaska regents]]\n[[Category:Women in Alaska politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Mary Jane Fate\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Mary Jane Evans\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1933|09|04}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rampart, Alaska|Rampart]], [[Territory of Alaska]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2020|04|10|1933|09|04}} <!--(death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place   = [[Fairbanks, Alaska|Fairbanks]], [[Alaska]]\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Native American activist\n| years_active  = 1962\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Mary Jane Fate''' (n\u00e9e Evans;  September 4, 1933 \u2014 April 10, 2020{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|2020}} is a [[Koyukon]] [[Alaskan Athabaskans|Athabascan]] activist. She was a founding member of the Fairbanks Native Association and the Institute of Alaska Native Arts and worked as a lobbyist for the [[Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act]]. She co-founded the ''[[Tundra Times]]'' newspaper and served as a director of the corporate board for [[Alaska Airlines]] for over two decades. She served as co-chair of the [[Alaska Federation of Natives]] between 1988 and 1989, the first woman to serve in the capacity, and was the third president and a founding member of the [[North American Indian Women's Association]]. Fate has served on various commissions and national studies of issues which affect indigenous people. She was the project manager of a study of women and disability, served as the only indigenous member of the U.S. Arctic Research Commission and was a member of U.S. Census Advisory Committee on indigenous populations. She has received numerous honors and awards for her activism on behalf of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] and  was inducted into the [[Alaska Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nMary Jane Evans was born in 1933 in [[Rampart, Alaska|Rampart]], in the United States [[Territory of Alaska]], to Sally (n\u00e9e Woods, later Hudson) and Thomas George Evans, Jr.{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|2012}} Her father was a trapper and mail carrier.{{sfn|''The Wausau Daily Herald''|1978|p=16}} After completing her primary education, Evans attended [[Mount Edgecumbe High School|Mount Edgecumbe]] [[American Indian boarding schools|Boarding School]] in Sitka, graduating in 1952.{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}{{sfn|''The Daily Sitka Sentinel''|1952|p=3}} She then went on to study accounting at the [[University of Alaska]] and simultaneously worked at [[Wien Air Alaska|Wien Alaska Airlines]] to pay her way through school.{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1962|p=11}} On 29 October 1954, she married Hugh Fate, Jr.,{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1954|p=5}}  who would become a dentist and Native Americans rights activist. The couple had three daughters, Janine, Jennifer and Julie.{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1969|p=10}}\n\n==Career==\nAfter her marriage, Fate returned to work at Wien Alaska Airlines.{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1962|p=11}} Fate and her husband were part of the founding members of the Fairbanks Native Association which organized in 1962 and 1963.{{sfn|Strickler|2011|p=76}}{{sfn|Morgan|2008|p=216}} Around the same time, she became involved in the ''[[Tundra Times]]'', the first news organization written by and for Native Alaskans, which served not only to inform the community of important issues throughout the state, but the state's congressional leaders of those issues the indigenous population felt were imperative. Fate was on the executive board of the paper and also served as the secretary to the board for the newspaper.{{sfn|Lueras|1974|p=6}}\n\nRecognizing the limited educational opportunities for Native Alaskans, Fate became involved in the Fairbanks Native Association's education committee {{sfn|Strickler|2011|p=76}}{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1964|p=9}} in 1962. She worked on a six-year study of the educational system to evaluate the reasons why education was substandard in Alaska. Fate testified at a state congressional hearing on their findings, showing that the majority of rural students either attended no high school or attended at inadequate facilities located long distances from their homes.{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|December 23, 1968|p=3}} The committee pressed for dormitories to be built for student housing in urban areas to enable students from rural areas to attend high schools.{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1966|p=3}} She served on the executive committee of the Native Alaskan Village for the [[Pioneer Park (Fairbanks, Alaska)|Alaska 67 Centennial Exposition]]{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1967|p=7}} and worked on the Hospital Foundation of Fairbanks,{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|February 15, 1968|p=7}} before becoming involved in the Alaska Native claims settlement. Provisions of the [[Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act]] (ANCSA) for the first time gave indigenous villages both land and capital to invest in education.{{sfn|Strickler|2011|p=76}} The settlement awarded 44 million acres of land and $962.5 million to allow Native Alaskans to establish twelve regional [[Alaska Native corporation|corporations]] to manage the assets.{{sfn|Strickler|2011|p=77}} Fate became president of the Rampart Village Corporation, established in 1971 as one of those regional entities{{sfn|Strickler|2011|p=76}} and worked to ensure that indigenous people enrolled to share in the settlement.{{sfn|''The San Saba News and Star''|1976|p=3}}\n\nFate was one of the founders of the [[North American Indian Women's Association]] (NAIWA) which formed in 1970 in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]].{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|1970}} The organization was the first [[pan-Indian]] group of indigenous women to organize with a national platform.{{sfn|''The Lawton Constitution''|1971|p=13}} In 1975, Fate became the third president of the NAIWA, succeeding [[Agnes Dill]].{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}{{sfn|''The Albuquerque Journal''|1975|p=24}} and served until 1977.{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|May 25, 1977|p=7}} Concern over the health of Native Alaskans was also an issue for Fate, and in the 1970s, she both spoke at conferences regarding the problems{{sfn|Jones|1970|p=1}} and with [[Nancy Murkowski]] and others founded a Breast Cancer Detection Center in Fairbanks in 1975.{{sfn|Monaghan|1976|p=9}}{{sfn|Miller|1998}} She headed a federal program ''Special Needs of Handicapped Indian Children and Indian Women's Problems'' which began in 1977, to collect and collate data concerning child abuse, nutrition, physical and mental handicaps, rape, single parenting, and violence towards women. In addition, the program evaluated social service availability to deal with these types of issues, including assessment of the facilities and qualifications required for caregivers.{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner|August 15, 1977|p=7}} In 1978, she participated in the national conference of Rural American Women Inc., held in Washington, D. C. The purpose of the meeting was to discuss problems faced by women, but specifically those, like isolation and lack of services, that compounded issues for women not living in urban centers.{{sfn|''The Great Falls Tribune''|1978|p=10}}\n\nIn 1981 Fate was appointed to serve on the Alaska Judicial Council and served until 1987.{{sfn|''The Daily Sitka Sentinel''|1993|p=9}} She was elected as co-chair with Henry Ivanoff of the Alaska Federation of Natives between 1988 and 1989 and was the first woman to hold the post.{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}{{sfn|''The Daily Sitka Sentinel''|1988|p=10}}{{sfn|''The Daily Sitka Sentinel''|1989|p=1}} In 1990, she was named to the Alaska Natives Commission and two years later was elected co-chair the commission with Perry Eaton. The goal of the commission, part of the joint Federal-State Commission on Policies and Programs Effecting Alaska Natives, was to complete a two-year study and make recommendations for a strategic plan for governmental interaction with native populations.{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}{{sfn|''The Daily Sitka Sentinel''|1993|p=9}} In 1991, Fate served on the transition team for governor-elect [[Wally Hickel]] and in 1993, was named to serve on the Board of Regents for the [[University of Alaska]].{{sfn|''The Daily Sitka Sentinel''|1993|p=9}}\n\nIn 1998, Fate received the national Cancer Awareness Award from the Congressional Families Action for Cancer Awareness for her work in health care.{{sfn|Miller|1998}} She was named by President [[George H.W. Bush]] to serve on the [[United States Arctic Research Commission]] in 2001. The commission's purpose, was to establish national scientific research policy for the [[Arctic region]], which was sensitive to residents and natural resources. Fate was the only Native American who served on the commission during her term which lasted until 2006. In 2003, she was appointed by President [[George W. Bush]] to serve on the U.S. Census Advisory Committee on American Indian and Alaska Native Populations.{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}} In 2012 Fate was honored by the [[Alaska Federation of Natives]] with two President's Awards, receiving both the Public Service Award and the Citizen of the Year Award,{{sfn|''The Fairbanks Daily News-Miner''|2012}} the highest honor the board bestows.{{sfn|Lean|2012}} She was inducted into the [[Alaska Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2014.{{sfn|Alaska Women's Hall of Fame|2014}}\n\n== References ==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n*{{cite news|ref=harv|last1=Gardiner|first1=Alistair|date=10 April 2020|title=Mary Jane Fate, who strove to improve life for Alaska Natives, dies|url=http://www.newsminer.com/alerts/mary-jane-fate-who-strove-to-improve-life-for-alaska-natives-dies/article_92f833d4-7dfd-11ea-ab6e-c3f305a91fef.html|location=Fairbanks, AK|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|access-date=16 April 2020}}\n*{{cite news|ref=harv|last1=Jones|first1=Tyler|title=Public seminar scheduled|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13290616/fairbanks_daily_newsminer/|accessdate=24 August 2017|newspaper=[[Fairbanks Daily News-Miner]]|date=August 19, 1970|location=Fairbanks, Alaska|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}\n*{{cite news|ref=harv|last1=Lean|first1=Reba|